# Kung Fu Chess ‚Äî Project Rules

Source: Kung Fu Chess Design Guide (course specification).

## Purpose

Kung Fu Chess is a real-time chess-like game. Pieces follow chess movement patterns, but moves are not instantaneous. A player selects a piece and clicks a destination; the piece travels at a fixed speed.

Build with test-driven, layered design. Keep game logic independent of rendering. Use simulated time (`wait(ms)`), never real sleep in tests.

---

## Game Scope (Common Route)

- Board is any rectangular size inferred from a textual description.
- Pieces use chess letters: `K`, `Q`, `R`, `B`, `N`, `P`.
- Color prefix: `w` (white), `b` (black). Example: `wK`, `bR`.
- `.` means an empty square.
- **Not implemented:** check, checkmate, castling, en passant, promotion.
- A king **can** be captured.
- Capturing the opponent king **ends the game**.
- A piece moves only according to its movement rule.
- Sliding pieces do not pass through blocking pieces.
- Movement has a fixed speed (see Timing).
- Tests use a fixed cell size in pixels.
- UI rendering uses only the supplied drawing/image library.
- The **logical board changes only when a moving piece arrives**.
- **One active motion at a time** (common route). If a legal-looking move is requested while a motion is already active, `GameEngine` rejects with reason `"motion_in_progress"`. No new motion starts; `Board` remains unchanged.
- Text integration DSL contains only: `Board`, `click`, `wait`, `print board`.
- `print board` is the **only** integration-test assertion mechanism.

### Extra Route (optional extensions ‚Äî only after common route is complete)

Allowed extra features (one per strong team): simultaneous movement, cooldown after movement, collision between moving pieces, cancellation when destination becomes occupied before arrival, replay file support, basic bot strategy, visual polish without changing the model.

Extra features must extend the appropriate layer without reversing dependency direction or merging unrelated responsibilities.

---

## Piece Movement Rules

Each piece type validates destinations via `PieceRules`. Rules are **stateless** ‚Äî they only calculate legal destinations from board + piece; they do not capture, move, or mutate.

| Piece  | Movement |
|--------|----------|
| Rook   | Horizontal and vertical sliding until blocked |
| Bishop | Diagonal sliding until blocked |
| Queen  | Rook + bishop movement |
| Knight | L-shaped jumps, ignoring blockers |
| King   | One square in any direction |
| Pawn   | Simplified forward movement (see below) |

### Pawn (simplified)

- White pawn moves **one row upward**.
- Black pawn moves **one row downward**.
- Pawn captures **one diagonal step forward**.
- **No** initial two-step move.
- **No** en passant.
- **No** promotion.

### RuleEngine validation

Given source cell and destination cell, `RuleEngine` answers: is this command legal now?

Reject:
- Moves outside the board
- Move attempts from empty cells
- Moving to a friendly-occupied destination
- Destinations illegal for the piece type

`MoveValidation`: `{ is_valid: bool, reason: string }`

Stable rule-level reasons: `"ok"`, `"outside_board"`, `"empty_source"`, `"friendly_destination"`, `"illegal_piece_move"`.

`RuleEngine` is **read-only** ‚Äî it does not move pieces, remove captures, start motions, or update game state.

Win condition: **king capture** (not checkmate).

---

## Real-Time Movement

Isolated in `RealTimeArbiter`. Active motions live **outside** `Board`.

### Constants

- `CELL_SIZE = 100` pixels
- `PIECE_SPEED = 100` pixels per second

### Timing

- Moving **1 square** takes **1000 ms**.
- Moving **2 squares** takes **2000 ms**.
- Moving **N squares** takes **N √ó 1000 ms**.
- Diagonal movement uses **cell-step duration**, not Euclidean pixel distance.
- Example: bishop 1 diagonal = 1000 ms; bishop 3 diagonal = 3000 ms.

### Logical board update

- A moving piece remains logically on its **source cell** until it arrives.
- Before arrival: `print board` shows the old board.
- At or after arrival: `print board` shows the updated board.
- Renderer may draw interpolated positions; logical board updates only on arrival.

### Arrival

When a moving piece arrives (atomic):
1. Remove it from the source cell.
2. Capture the enemy at the destination (if any).
3. Place the moving piece at the destination.
4. If captured piece is a king ‚Üí report king capture to `GameEngine` ‚Üí set `game_over`.

### GameEngine motion policy

- Reject `request_move` when `game_over` ‚Üí reason `"game_over"`.
- Reject `request_move` when a motion is active ‚Üí reason `"motion_in_progress"`.
- `wait(ms)` delegates to `RealTimeArbiter.advance_time(ms)`; must not directly manipulate board motion state.

`MoveResult`: `{ is_accepted: bool, reason: string }`

---

## Controller

Translates clicks into game commands. **Does not** decide chess legality.

- Convert pixels to cells via `BoardMapper`: `col = x // 100`, `row = y // 100`.
- First click: select a piece (ignore empty cells).
- Second in-board click: call `GameEngine.request_move(source, destination)`.
- Clear selection after every second in-board click (legal or illegal).
- No selection + outside-board click ‚Üí ignore.
- Selection active + outside-board click ‚Üí cancel selection, no command.
- **Must not** call `Board.move_piece` or `RuleEngine` directly.

Click examples (`CELL_SIZE = 100`):
- `click 50 50` ‚Üí row 0, col 0
- `click 150 50` ‚Üí row 0, col 1
- `click 50 150` ‚Üí row 1, col 0

---

## Architecture Layers

| Layer | Owns | Must NOT own |
|-------|------|--------------|
| **Model** (`Board`, `Position`, `Piece`, `GameState`) | Coordinates, piece identity, logical occupancy, lifecycle state | Pixels, clicks, rendering, rules, timing |
| **PieceRules** | Movement geometry per piece type | Commands, time, animation, rendering |
| **RuleEngine** | Read-only legality validation | Board mutation, animation, game-over |
| **GameEngine** | Coordination: game-over guard, validation delegation, starting motions, wait, snapshots | Piece-specific logic, rendering, input parsing, DSL |
| **RealTimeArbiter** | Active `Motion` objects, time advancement, arrival resolution, captures | Chess legality, clicks, rendering |
| **Controller** | Click interpretation, selection state | Legality, board mutation, timing |
| **Renderer** | Visual drawing from read-only `GameSnapshot` | Rules, board mutation, input |
| **Text I/O** (`BoardParser`, `BoardPrinter`) | Textual setup and logical board output | Movement rules, command execution |
| **TextTestRunner** | Script parsing, driving public command path | Movement rules, direct board mutation |

Dependency direction: **Model ‚Üê Rules ‚Üê Engine ‚Üê Controller/Tests**. View depends on snapshots only. Never point dependencies from model to UI.

`GameEngine` is the application-service coordinator and public command boundary.

There is no `model/move.py` in the common route. Move requests are source + destination at the API boundary.

---

## Package Structure

```
kungfu_chess/
  model/       position.py, piece.py, board.py, game_state.py
  rules/       piece_rules.py, rule_engine.py, rules_loader.py, path_utils.py, rules.json
  realtime/    motion.py, real_time_arbiter.py
  engine/      game_engine.py
  input/       board_mapper.py, controller.py
  io/          board_parser.py, board_printer.py
  view/        renderer.py
  texttests/   script_runner.py
  app.py
tests/unit/
```

Entry point: `main.py` ‚Üí `p_input.py` ‚Üí `kungfu_chess/texttests/script_runner.py`

---

## Text Integration Test DSL

Commands (exactly four):

```
Board
<textual board rows>
click <x> <y>
wait <milliseconds>
print board
<expected board rows>
```

### Board notation

- One row per line, cells separated by spaces.
- `.` = empty, `w`/`b` prefix for color, piece letter = chess notation.
- Width/height inferred from text; all rows must have same cell count.

### Assertion strategy

Only `print board` + expected rows. Covers: parsing, pixel mapping, legal/illegal moves, partial/full wait, blocking, capture, king capture / game over.

Selection state is tested by unit tests only (not in `print board`).

### Text test flow (required)

```
Board text ‚Üí BoardParser ‚Üí GameEngine
click      ‚Üí Controller.click(x, y)
wait       ‚Üí GameEngine.wait(ms)
print board ‚Üí BoardPrinter.print(game_state)
```

**Forbidden:** `ScriptRunner` directly calling `Board.move_piece` (bypasses controller, engine, rules, arbiter).

---

## Public API Between Layers

- `BoardParser.parse(text) -> Board`
- `BoardPrinter.print(game_state | snapshot) -> text`
- `BoardMapper.pixel_to_cell(x, y) -> Position | None`
- `Controller.click(x, y) -> ControllerResult`
- `GameEngine.request_move(source, destination) -> MoveResult`
- `GameEngine.wait(ms) -> None`
- `GameEngine.snapshot() -> GameSnapshot`
- `RuleEngine.validate_move(board, source, destination) -> MoveValidation`
- `RealTimeArbiter.has_active_motion() -> bool`
- `RealTimeArbiter.start_motion(piece, source, destination) -> None`
- `RealTimeArbiter.advance_time(ms) -> ArrivalEvents`

---

## Development Loop

```
Requirement ‚Üí test plan ‚Üí failing tests ‚Üí implementation ‚Üí refactor ‚Üí review ‚Üí commit
```

- Write unit tests for pure logic before connecting UI.
- Use fake clocks / `wait(ms)`, never real sleep.
- Keep rendering thin and replaceable.
- Avoid hidden global state; small classes with clear responsibility.
- Commit only when tests pass.
- When using an LLM: small reviewable steps, one layer at a time, verify with tests.

### Definition of done (per feature)

1. Unit tests cover internal logic.
2. At least one text integration test covers user-visible behavior via `print board`.
3. No UI dependency in model.
4. No real time in tests.
5. Small, reviewable diff with clear layer ownership.

---

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- Pixels in model (belong in `BoardMapper` / renderer)
- Chess rules in controller (belong in `RuleEngine` / `PieceRules`)
- Real sleep in tests
- `print board` depending on rendering (logical state only)
- `RuleEngine` mutating `Board`
- Active `Motion` objects inside `Board`
- Live `Board`/`Piece` objects passed to `Renderer` (use `GameSnapshot`)
- Second move while motion active (reject with `"motion_in_progress"`)
- `BoardParser` hidden inside `texttests` (shared I/O adapter)
- Game-over moves still mutating board (reject with `"game_over"`)
